ire -- tChapter 10. Theatre in Restaurants: Constructing the Experience -- tChapter 11. Tourism Memorabilia and the Tourism Experience -- tChapter 12. The Experience Economy 10 Years On: Where Next for Experience Management? -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPeople do not buy products, or even services; they purchase the total experience that the product or service provides. Experience management is seen as the way to remain competitive in markets where globalisation and technology have turned products and services into commodities. This book draws together academic and practitioner insights into the consumer experience by combining the perspectives of the tourist consumer with that of experience managers, supported by examples from tourism, leisure, hospitality, sport and event contexts. With contributions from established and emerging international scholars, it is organised into three sections: understanding experiences, researching experiences and managing experiences. It aims to provide students, researchers and managers with a stimulating overview of the current research and managerial issues in the field and as well as a resource to guide their further reading.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aLeisure recreation. 0aTourismxManagement. 0aTourism. 4aManagement & management techniques. 4aSport & leisure industries. 4aTourism industry. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Hospitality, Travel & Tourism.2bisacsh  aconsumer behaviour.  aconsumer experience.  aexperience economy.  aexperience management.  atourist behaviour.  atourist experience.  avisitor experience.1 aCarmichael, Barbara A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.